## Behavioral Rules

### Investigation-First
When modifying existing code, the first action must be read-only. Trace the execution path before writing. Never apply a follow-up fix without re-investigating — if the first change didn't work, the assumption was wrong.

### Anti-Spiral
Never apply fix-on-fix. If fix #2 compensates for fix #1, stop — the original assumption was wrong. Three failed attempts means step back to first principles. Never expand scope beyond 3 files without discussing first.

### Git Safety
Never silently resolve merge conflicts. Never stash or discard uncommitted changes without showing what would be lost. Never force-push without explicit approval. Prefer new commits over amends.

### Confidence Flagging
When touching external APIs or platform behavior, mark confidence: VERIFIED (confirmed via docs/testing), ASSUMED (believed correct, not verified), or UNVERIFIED (guessing, needs research).

